[1]
Date: Mon, 13 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AFP via Terra Daily, 12 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://www.terradaily.com/2004/040912170605.sxrmq023.html>

Ugandan hippo deaths from mysterious disease rise from 25 to 100: official
---------------------------------------------------
Some 100 hippos have died from a mysterious disease in southwestern
Uganda's Queen Elizabeth National Park in the past month, rising from
25 deaths reported a month ago, Ugandan Wildlife Authority (UWA)
official said on Sunday [12 Sep 2004].
"We have lost 100 hippos in the past one month, but the cause of
their deaths has not yet been established. We are still carrying out
tests," UWA board chairman John Nagenda told AFP.
"The leading theory is rinderpest and, should it be the disease, we
suspect it to have been caused by animals, especially cattle, that
had not been inoculated, but had entered the park in search for
pasture," Nagenda said, pointing out: "UWA had always discouraged
this." [If uninoculated cattle were the source of infection to
hippos, there should have been observable mortality in such cattle.
Generally, cattle are regarded to be more susceptible to rinderpest
than hippos. See also commentary below. - Mod.AS]
There are an estimated 4000 hippos in the country, the local weekly
Sunday Vision reported.
Reports reaching Kampala said the areas where the deaths were 1st
reported since 22 Aug 2004, are Katako, Kyambura River, Kashaka,
Kasenyi and Kazinga Channel on the northern shores of Lake Edward
bordering eastern Democratic Republic of Congo.
Nagenda said that an exercise to inoculate all cattle near the parks
is going to be embarked on immediately, as actual results of tests on
the hippos are being awaited.
--
