[2]
Date: Mon, 13 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhuanet.com, 13 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2004-09/13/content_1976214.htm>

4 die after eating dead hippo's meat in western Uganda
-------------------------------------------------
4 people in western Uganda died recently after they reportedly ate a
dead hippo's meat, The New Vision newspaper reported on Monday [13
Sep 2004].
The dead, from Bunyaruguru county, Bushenyi district, ate the meat
after the hippo died of a strange disease. 3 more [who] ate [have
been] hospitalized at Rugazi Health Center, the report said. [Results
of postmortem investigations, if carried out, and of the clinical
observations and lab tests of the hospitalised patients, particularly
their response to antibiotic (penicillin?) treatment, will be
helpful. - Mod.AS]
Bushenyi district director of health services Charles Katurebe said
they were investigating the deaths.
Bunyaruguru county residents have always complained that hippos from
Queen Elizabeth National Park eat their crops.
A mysterious disease hitting Queen Elizabeth National Park in western
Uganda about a month ago has killed more than 100 hippos out of an
estimated 4000 to date.
The Uganda Wildlife Authority (UWA) dispatched an expert team made up
of people from the UWA, Makerere University, the Ministry of
Agriculture and an European Union supported disease control program
in mid-August to investigate the deaths.
However, the cause of the deaths remains a mystery.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There is serologic evidence for the susceptibility of hippos to
infection with the rinderpest virus; however, no clear data on their
clinical susceptibility could be found. Readers who might have such
data are invited to forward them.
On the other hand, sickness and death in humans following the
consumption of meat from diseased animals might indicate a zoonosis,
most probably anthrax, or -- less likely -- a toxic agent. Rinderpest
does not affect humans.
One remark in the news item, namely that "Bunyaruguru county
residents have always complained that hippos from Queen Elizabeth
National Park eat their crops", might indicate that deliberate
poisoning is a possibility, though rather a remote one, in view of
the wide geographic spread of cases.
Results of the current investigations by the Ugandan/EU experts team,
or data on samples already obtained, will be helpful. - Mod.AS]
